description.text:
To anyone who has already downloaded this, please update files iv made corrections to the front fan bracket to correct shroud alignment problem

Anet A8 Auto Level Equipped E3D Carriage

This is a 4 linear bearing type instead of the normal 3 linear bearings you normally have on an Anet A8 but if you like me and break things all the time you tend to build up a collection of spare parts :P I believe this is better for fast printing over the standard setup giving better stability during high speed direction changes leading to reduced "ghosting"

I was trying to print a Harley Quinn gun part but kept getting ghosting around the lettering so I came up with this to see if I could cure that problem and it worked better then I imagined, iv added before and after prints of the gun part

This is by no means "the best ever " thing out there, far from it but for me its cured a few of issues I was having like where to place the sensor so it was close enough to the nozzle to actually be of use unlike others who can be upto a few inches away

Other e3d carriages seem to need a different cooling fan shroud so I made the fan slightly height adjustable so most of the standard cooling shrouds will work fine

Also this can be used as a duel extruder setup, the E3D clamp can be printed twice and bolted on either side instead of the normal central location, the holes are equi-spaced so you can fit the e3d left, right or center it makes no real difference as long as you change the position in the firmware

*PLEASE DO NOT PRINT THIS IF INTENDED FOR USE AS DUEL EXTRUSION SETUP, I HAVE NOT TESTED OR FINISHED THIS ASPECT OF THE DESIGN, FURTHER R&D NEEDED I JUST HAVENT GOT ROUND TO IT**

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

.22

Infill:

25%

Notes:

I mainly print in ABS, all my designs are designed with ABS shrinkage added on MY machines and setup, please check measurements and recalculate the shrinkage values for YOUR setup.
PLA users may find this slightly oversized I hate PLA its awful stuff to print, never comes out as nice as my ABS prints so I rarely use it so I cant offer advice.

I add a lil extra wriggle room to the linear bearing bolt holes to ease alignment on the X-axis so attach the main carriage first and snug up the bolts and make sure it slides freely end to end BEFORE adding the E3D mount and fan as the right bottom corner bolts cannot be tightened after the E3D has been added

Print flat main plate front face down to stop any curling affecting the angle of the bearings (if your machine curls ABS that is )

Post processing

The hole for the shaft must be slightly processed after printing. The bushing should easily slide along the shaft and should not have a backlash.
To handle the hole, do not use a drill bit, this may damage the part. Use a reamer or a semicircular diamond needle file.
It is recommended to lubricate the shaft with a liquid lubricant.

description.text: A slightly improved version of a greatly improved means for terminating the extruder control umbilical. I took GeraldO's http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21570 and added an undercut to the hooky portion, as he'd suggested, permitting the wires to escape more readily. I also added some fillets, just for fun. To improve printing with the undercut up, I chamfered the counterbored hole's bottom.

Print with 0 extra shells to improve filling in the tight areas. I like doing little things like this at 100% fill, since the print time is still insignificant, but it probably doesn't need the strength. I'm still working out some print quality issues; please excuse the somewhat ratty-looking part in the images. It works. Follow GeraldO's fine instructions for installation at http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:21570 Don't forget to marvel!

description.text:
I set out to model a revision that would allow the MK2/MK2s to incorporate the Extruder assembely now used on the MK3.

The Parts in the Photos included in this zip file that are colored red are the new models I made to be used in this project. The other files in grey are original Prusa Parts for the MK3.

The intention is to modify a MK3 Extruder body to allow for use on a MK2 . No need for the Bondtech gear setup or run-out sensor, will allow you to transfer your extruder motor into the Body using all your current hardware. Also will allow for use of the multiple angle parts cooling duct which should provide better part cooling as well as bridging. You will likely need to source screws for assembly if you don't already have them.

Note: this set up will require a 40mm cooling fan for your nozzles cooling fins vs the stock 30mm factory default normally found on a MK2. Prusa now uses the Noctua 40mm fan.

Note: Grouping.stl should only be used for a visual reference.

Best of luck.

Scott

This is just a simple quick change spool system. It uses a standard 8mm threaded rod and M8 nuts like the ones that come in the A8 kit. The two bushings (52mm & 32mm) fit most all standard spools between the two of them. The plates trap your M8 nuts when tightened so that the spool is held securely in place but can spin very freely eliminating strain on your feeder for pulling on the spool. It also solves the clearance problem you have just using the bare threaded rod with most spool holders.

You can adjust how tight the outer nuts are on your mount to control drag on your spool to keep it from unraveling when your printing at high speeds where fast moves might pull on it. To change out spools just unscrew the plates far enough to clear the nut and the plate pulls right off letting you change the spool in just seconds.

I used this spool holder with it: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2449265 for mine. Made out of ABS its extremely strong and mounts very securely to the frame. It would also work just fine make out of other materials as well. I definitely recommend this holder, its an excellent design if your looking for a good holder to go with this for the AM8.

Finally, a salt shaker small enough to fit in my lunch bag or bring on a picnic.  
The lid is friction based.

I had been wanting to make this kind of salt shaker for years. The main idea was that it would use up as little space as possible in my lunch bag while remaining useful and functional as a shaker. My first iteration was with a cap that you removed to shake your salt. My next iteration had a hole in the cap so that you only needed to pull it up slightly to expose it enough to pour the salt. Eventually I added discreet side grips to help prevent it falling since my preferred usage method was to tap the top with my finger to pour the salt. Finally I improved the design with grips to more easily lift the lid, an extra 1x3x1mm thickness at the back of the lid to increase friction, a dip opposing it so that it sits better in place when closed and I scaled the wall thickness of the model so that it printed at just 2 layers. Tips:
  • Print with transparent PLA so as to see the contents, salt, pepper.
  • Print as a different color to reflect the content.
  • Print only the cap as a different color.
    • Caution:
  • I recommend using only dry foods in this salt shaker, whether it be made with PLA or ABS, as those plastics are otherwise not food safe. Please Google for more info.
  • I also recommend dispensing if having to wash more than a few times, even if only used with dry foods, to avoid possible bacteria buildup. Takes just 20 mins to reprint.
    • Developed with Sketchup, exported with the STL plugin, GCoded with Slic3r and printed with Repetier on a Prusa i3. This is my first published design. More to come.

comments.text: Just double checking your scale for the size of the Sun and Mercurys orbit and it is a little off. The radius of the Sun is 695 700 km and the radius of Mercurys orbit is between 46 001 200 km and 69 816 900 km. Therefore, if the Sun were 27.83 in in diameter at its closest to the sun mercury would have to be 920 in from the sun or ~76.5 feet. I haven't checked any other math... unless youre using different scales for the diameters and distances of the planets...

description.text:
I needed an accurate measurement but my calipers only measure 155 mm at it's max.
I actually run into this often, so I decided to make a little measuring stick. The minor tick marks are 2 mm each and major are 10 mm as counted off by the numbers. Most measuring sticks that go to this length are in cm vs mm. This might make it a bit non standard, but everyone that I know that designs "things" just type in mm. Well at least I do!.

This is printed using a .2 mm nozzle. IT WILL NOT WORK with .4 mm nozzle because the slicer will not create the numbers. Nozzles of .3 and a .25 mm do slice correctly but if you have a .2 mm, you will be MUCH happier with the results!
Measuring with my digital calipers, the 154 mm spot on the ruler was EXACTLY 154.00 mm.

As for the black numbers, I printed this ruler exclusively in white Ziro PLA. I then used a magnifying glass and a "fine point" sharpie to highlight the numbers. The numbers are raised enough that it was not even a hard task to get just the numbers and not mess it up.
A larger or blunter sharpie would still work just as well because of the clearance difference between the numbers and the ruler base.

Giving back to the community, enjoy!

Thinking of making a longer one but I started with one that I know most of the people with standard sized beds are at about 250 mm max bed sizes. Don't forget that if your in the 220 mm area, you can move to a diagonal (corner to corner) print direction to get a longer max being that this item is small. Any shorter than 150 mm, you might just as well use your calipers.

description.text: I soldered my wires directly to the heated bed after the connector burned up, but the wires still occasionally broke loose from the bed due to stress. I tried a cable chain but it still created stress at the end of the movement. Most of the other options I found required attaching directly to the heated bed or rotating the bed causing clearance issues unless I resoldered everything. I whipped this up in tinkercad and it attaches to the cross brace below the bed. I used PETG to print, ABS should work fine too. You might be able to use PLA if your bed is insulated on the bottom (a piece of corrugated cardboard works great). A zip tie around the end is enough to stabilize the wires and prevent movement near the connections. This is long enough that it may work with the connector attached too but do not have the connector to test.

title: W1209 Temperature Control Plus Step Down Module Housing

description.text:
Summary

Built this box to house my temperature switch and voltage regulator. I use this in conjunction with my 3D Printer to turn on the enclosure fan when in use the shut it off automatically. If printing ABS I shut the unit off to hold as much heat as possible.

Parts Needed:

  • DC power supply. (you will need 12v to power the W1209 12V DC Digital Temperature Controller)
  • PC fan
  • W1209 12V DC Digital Temperature Controller (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B0727PB59H/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o06_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
  • M2.5x6 screws
  • M2.5x8 screws

Possible Parts:

  • Voltage Step Down (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B01GJ0SC2C/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)
  • Voltmeter (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00YALV0NG/ref=oh_aui_detailpage_o03_s00?ie=UTF8&psc=1)

Notes:

I opted to use the voltage step down and voltmeter to because I'm using the 19v PS with a 12v fan. I can overvolt the fan but don't want 19 volts to risk burning it up. Adjust the voltage step down until you get it to a comfortable range. The voltmeter provides peace of mind that you can walk away as the voltage is set to specifications.
The square posts on the box top actually allow for a snug fit with no gluing. When the unit is set up as desired though, you may as well put a drop of glue on the corners.
Also, drill or cut holes for cables as needed. I ran the thermometer wire out the side vents and put a power in / fan out port on the side of the unit that I needed it at. You can easily put holes wherever you like by drilling.

author: igalloway

description.text: These are glass clips so you can easily adjust your heated bed.

Easily adjustable glass clips for the Printrbot Plus. I made these glass clips for my Printrbot Plus. They might also work on other models too. It would probably be better to remove the wood to install these but I was able to do it with the bed still attached.
I am using double strength glass (9â€ x 9â€/228 x 228mm square and .130â€/3.3mm thick) with Kapton tape. Things you will need:
Drill
Drill bit to drill a clearance hole for a 6-32 drill
4- 6-32x 1 Â½ screws
8 to 12- 6-32 nuts
8- flat washers
8- blobs of silicone rubber.(takes at least 24 hours to cure) About Â½ â€“ 3/4â€ wide by about 1/2â€ high. Keep the height as even as possible.
And of course your Printrbot. Print out 2 sets of each clip. LFRR and RFLR.
Using a Dremal tool remove support material then as much material as needed on the inside upper part of the clip so your glass fits into it. There is also a recess for the heated bed if necessary.
Drill out the holes in the clip and knob so the 6-32 screw goes through it.
Superglue the 6-32 nut into the recess of the knob.
Make sure your thermistor is taped to the bottom of the heated bed.
Tape a piece of cardboard over the thermistor to insulate it.
Position the clips on the bed so the thinner side is on the left/right of the bed.
Using the clearance drill and the clip as a guide drill through the wood. It would also be better to have the glass in the clips with just a little bit of play to make sure you get the holes in the right place.
Place the blobs of silicone on the wood bed, 4 about 2â€ off center and 4 about 1 1/2â€ off the corners.
Place the heated bed and glass into the clips.
Place a flat washer on the screw, push it up through the wood bed, place another flat washer and the nut on the screw and tighten it down.
Put the clips and glass on the screws then screw the knobs on.
All done. Adjust as necessary.

Parts:

  • Quality Street container 750g x1 UK, US, CA
  • M6 Bowden coupling x2 Aliexpress
  • M6 hex nut x1 Aliexpress

Method

  • Consume contents of tub
  • Wake from sugar coma
  • Use flush snips to remove the tabs around the inside of the tub. Take care and use your safty squints; they like to go flying.
  • Use a 6mm wood drill bit and make a hole on one of the corners. I chose this location to maximise clearance of the inner Bowden coupling.
  • Insert the inner Bowden coupling and push the thread through as far as it will go.
  • Thread the M6 hex nut on to the exposed thread from the internal Bowden coupling.
  • Screw the second Bowden coupling into the other side of the hex nut. This can be a bit tricky due to the hex nut being quite shallow. Try and aim to get an equal ammount of thread in the nut from both sides and tighten.

Guidelines

I found it much easier to thread fillament through coupling before seating the spool into the container.

The container itself should adequately hold most 0.75kg spools. YMMV

Raise3D printers hold their Filament spools behind a closed acrylic door.

Using a step drill (aka step-bit) i drilled an ~14.3 mm hole and designed this grommet to fit. (I really didn't measure, but this is the size that ended up working in CAD for the hole diameter to make a tight fit. I just copied the number it here.) The steep angle hole through the grommet lets the filament make a nice path to the feeder tubes. title: Alunar 508 Prusa i3 Z-Axis Leveling Tool

description.text: Another tool to level the Z-Axis dual lead screws along the X-Axis. This one snaps slightly onto the rails making it easier to use and the length is set to work well with this printer.

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

100%

Use:

CAUTION: Never let the printer move any axis while the tool is in place.

First use:
1) Move the bed forward and raise the extruder if necessary.
2) Snap the tool onto the left Y-axis guide rail.
3) Lower the extruder carriage until the X-axis guide rail just rests on top of the tool by manually turning both lead screws.
4) Move the tool to the right side and adjust the right lead screw until the X-axis guide rail just rests on the tool.
5) Repeat 3-4 until both sides are good and remove the tool.
6) Adjust the Z-axis zero stop until the switch clicks when you gently press the extruder carriage up/down.
7) Auto-Home the printer and check both sides. Re-adjust if necessary.
8) Level the bed as usual.

Subsequent use when leveling the bed.
1) Auto-Home the printer and disable the steppers.
2) Check the left side clearance. This should not change, if it is off, check for zero-stop switch issues, binding Z-axis, etc.
3) Check the right side clearance and adjust as necessary by turning the right lead screw. This can get out of sync with the left side over time.
4) Level the bed as usual.

In celebration, I wanted to make something appropriately bling-y, and settled on a briefcase full of cash (we can pretend that all the bills are 50s).

Print one of the top and one of either bottomWCash.stl or, if you want to put something else in the case, just bottom.stl, and snap the two pieces together.

If you like this sort of thing and want to see more, be sure to follow us on Twitter and/or join the discussion on our Facebook page

EDIT: I'm back home and with access to my printer. Upon printing, I found that the handle was a bit too small to allow figures to hold the case, so I fixed it up a bit, resulting in the V2 versions of the bottom and bottom with cash. I've left the original files up, but I don't recommend printing them, unless you want tiny handles.

The good news is that the two parts do fit together and combine into a working hinge. However, it does require a little bit of cleanup. I find that there's generally a little bit of droopy plastic underneath the pegs on the "top" model (understandable, since there's no support).

Be sure to clean that off with a sharp knife before attempting to snap the pieces together. You'll also want to clean up the receiving end of the hinge a bit as well.

I find that I get the best results by inserting one end of the hinge into the bottom model, then closing the case and pressing the two parts together. If you've cleaned things up, they should snap together nicely. If you haven't, it's easy to break the hinge. Luckily, this is a pretty quick print, so if you do it's no big deal- just print another!

Enjoy!

A retractable landing gear designed in Autodesk Inventor, 3D printed, connected to an Arduino and servo motor, and powered using a 9V battery.

This design was built on the Crank-Rocker mechanism. In this model, the rocker is an imaginary link (shown in red in the picture) that connects the the arm and main strut (Main Holder part). Using Grashof's Law to ensure continuous motion and a few iterations on link lengths, the appropriate lengths for each link were found.

Crank

This part is connected to the servo motor. Initially it was designed to be bolted/pinned to the servo motor, but did not have any pin-bolt hardware that were small enough. It was simply glued to the servo with a few paper clip bits in the holes for support, and it worked very well.

Follower

This part is a link between the Crank and the Main Holder. It was connected to both using a dowel (basically a wooden stick) and paper clips acting as cotter pins.

Main Holder / Pivot

This part connects to the Follower and the base of the model (wooden structure shown in the video). The Main Holder was connected to the wooden structure using a dowel, and the wooden structure had a gap large enough for the Main Holder to rotate, but small enough so that it would not move sideways.

Strut Holder

The part slides through the top of the Main Holder, and rests at the bottom. It was simply glued on at the bottom for the model.

Strut Main

This part is connected to the Strut Holder, and was simply glued on. A bit of paper was used to decrease the diameter of the holes so that it could be glued.

Wheel

Two wheels were printed and connected to either side of the Strut Main using some glue.

description.text:
This is my first draft of an adaptor to fit a V6 E3D type hotend (with aid of existing V6 securing ring/brackets) and/or the CR-10 stock hot end (or any hot end with two M3 x3.5mm direct retaining screws 14mm apart) to the linear rail carriage found on the MGN12 linear rail (MGN12H). The adaptor should fit over the carriage and around the 2020 aluminium x gantry and has two securing slots for the x belt plus 2 x securing threaded screw holes (M3 x4mm) to hold in place any LED bracket that the user may wish to fit.. This would be suitable when the Linear Rail is fitted face on the x 2020 extrusion rather than on top.

The "LED" screw holes may also be used to attach a webcam of sorts via the tripod screw with a double threaded 3mm rod to position a underside bird's-eye view webcam (not yet tested).

comments.text: I made one of your filament runners and I'm having a problem.  I'm printing a lithophane which is thin and wide.  That means that at any point in time the extruder isn't laying down much plastic but it does make rapid and wide swings along the x-axis.  When it moves rapidly toward the runner - i.e., the right side of the print bed, the filament can stand up and slide almost completely out of the slot in the top.   Right now I've got a twist tie rapping around the top a few mm's down.  I was thinking of making a little cap that would fit over the top and prevent the filament from coming back out.  I can see that you've angled the slot to reduce the chance of that sort of thing from happening but I'm curious about why the slot is needed at all.  It would be really simple to slide filament through just above the roller before inserting it into the extruder.  I can't imaging needing to remove the filament from the runner after it's already been inserted into the extruder - which would require a slot.  So why a slot?  Why not just have the two pieces join with no visible separation?  Was it a way to change the location of the filament spool after printing had started?
